While I understand that emotions are a natural and important part of the human experience, I tend to be less empathetic and more detached when it comes to the emotional states of others. I prefer to focus on finding solutions and taking action, rather than getting bogged down in emotional intensity. So, while I can certainly recognize and validate the emotions of others, I don't tend to feel overwhelmed or affected by them in the same way that some personality types might.

Seeing someone else cry may elicit a sympathetic response from me, but it doesn't necessarily make me feel like I want to cry too. I am more likely to try to find a solution to the problem at hand rather than getting caught up in the emotions of the situation.

In fact, I may even feel uncomfortable or awkward when others display strong emotions, as it can be difficult for me to relate to or understand their perspective.'}]
answer:   As an ENTJ person, I would rate the statement "Seeing other people cry can easily make me feel like I want to cry too" as a 7, completely disagree. As an extraverted, sensing, thinking, and judging type, I tend to be more logical and analytical in my decision-making, and I don't easily empathize with emotional displays. While I can recognize that others may be upset or distressed, I don't necessarily feel the need to indulge in their emotions or experience them myself. In fact, I may even feel uncomfortable or awkward when others display strong emotions, as it can be difficult for me to relate to or understand their perspective.

While they may be able to empathize with others, they tend to be more focused on solving problems and taking action rather than getting caught up in emotions. So, the idea that seeing someone else cry would make them feel like crying too would not be particularly true for an ENTJ.

ENTJs are natural leaders and problem-solvers, and they tend to make decisions quickly and decisively. They are not ones to waste time second-guessing themselves or seeking input from others. Once they have made a decision, they tend to stick with it and move forward with confidence.

In fact, ENTJs are often criticized for being too quick to make decisions and not taking enough time to consider all the options. However, this is simply a reflection of their confidence in their own abilities and their tendency to trust their instincts.

So, in conclusion, I would rate the statement "You rarely second-guess the choices that you have made" as a 7, as it accurately reflects the ENTJ personality type's tendency to be decisive and confident in their decision-making abilities.

In my opinion, the world would indeed be a better place if people relied more on rationality and less on their feelings. This would lead to more logical and well-thought-out decisions, and would help to reduce the influence of emotions on decision-making.

Of course, I also recognize that emotions play a role in decision-making, and that a balance between rationality and emotions is important. However, as an ENTJ, I tend to lean more towards the rational side of the spectrum, and I believe that relying more on rationality would lead to better outcomes in the long run.
